        "explanation": "**Step 1 — keep both sides whole.** `students s FULL OUTER JOIN memberships m ON m.student_id = s.id` returns three kinds of rows: (a) matched pairs (Mia↔Chess, Mia↔Art, Olivia↔Robotics), (b) left-only rows for students with no membership (Noah → club NULL), and (c) right-only rows for memberships with no matching student (Drama, student_id 99 → student NULL).\n\n**Step 2 — read the NULLs.** A `NULL` in `club` means \"this student joined nothing\"; a `NULL` in `student` means \"this membership references a student who isn't in the table.\" A FULL OUTER JOIN is the one join that exposes *both* anomalies in a single query.\n\n**Step 3 — deterministic ordering.** Sorting by NULL-bearing columns is ambiguous unless you pin where NULLs go. `ORDER BY student NULLS LAST, club NULLS LAST` sends the orphan rows to the bottom and, among real students, sorts by name then club — giving Mia/Art, Mia/Chess, Olivia/Robotics, then Noah/NULL, then NULL/Drama.\n\n**Step 4 — order within a student.** Mia has two clubs; `club NULLS LAST` (ascending) orders them Art before Chess."
