        "sql": "SELECT c.name AS customer, SUM(oi.qty * oi.price) AS total_spent\nFROM customers c\nJOIN orders o ON o.customer_id = c.id\nJOIN order_items oi ON oi.order_id = o.id\nGROUP BY c.id, c.name\nORDER BY total_spent DESC, customer;",
        "explanation": "**Step 1 — chain the joins.** `customers c JOIN orders o ON o.customer_id = c.id` attaches each order to its customer; `JOIN order_items oi ON oi.order_id = o.id` then attaches each line item to its order. After both joins, there is exactly one row per *line item*, decorated with its order and customer.\n\n**Step 2 — compute the per-line value.** `oi.qty * oi.price` is the money for that single line. Ava's order 10 has Pen (3×2 = 6) and Book (1×10 = 10); her order 11 has Pen (5×2 = 10).\n\n**Step 3 — aggregate per customer.** `GROUP BY c.id, c.name` folds all of a customer's line-item rows together and `SUM(oi.qty * oi.price)` totals them: Ava 6+10+10 = 26, Ben 2×10 = 20, Cara 4×5 = 20.\n\n**Step 4 — why group on the id.** Grouping on the primary key `c.id` (not just the name) is the robust habit — two customers could share a name, and the id keeps them separate.\n\n**Step 5 — order.** `ORDER BY total_spent DESC, customer` puts the biggest spender first; Ben and Cara tie at 20, so the `customer` tiebreaker places Ben before Cara, giving one deterministic order."
